{{Conservatism US}}
'''Paleoconservatism''' (sometimes shortened to '''paleocon''') is a [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] [[political philosophy]] stressing [[tradition]], [[limited government|limited Federal government]] and [[civil society]], along with [[Christian values|religious]], [[Regionalism (politics)|regional]], [[Nationalism|national]] and [[Western world|Western]] identity.{{efn|For more discussion of defining elements of paleoconservative thought, see {{harvnb|Gottfried|1993}}, {{harvnb|Gottfried|2006}}, and {{harvnb|Scotchie|2017b}}.}}<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Williamson |first=Chilton, Jr. |date=January 2011 |title=What Is Paleoconservatism? Man, Know Thyself! |url=http://chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/January2001/0101WilliamsonPaleo.html |magazine=Chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041205111513/http://chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/January2001/0101WilliamsonPaleo.html |archive-date=December 5, 2004 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> 

According to the [[international relations]] scholar [[Michael Foley (academic)|Michael Foley]], "paleoconservatives press for restrictions on [[Immigration to the United States|immigration]], a rollback of [[Multiculturalism|multicultural]] programmes, the [[States' rights|decentralization of federal policy]], the restoration of [[Protectionism|controls upon free trade]], a greater emphasis upon [[economic nationalism]] and [[United States non-interventionism|non-interventionism in the conduct of American foreign policy]], and a generally [[Revanchism|revanchist]] outlook upon a social order in need of recovering old lines of distinction and in particular the assignment of roles in accordance with traditional categories of gender, ethnicity, and race".{{sfn|Foley|2007|p=318}} Practitioners of this philosophy identify themselves as the legitimate heirs to the American conservative tradition.{{sfn|Woltermann|1993}}

[[United States|American]] politician [[Pat Buchanan]] was strongly influenced by the Rockford Institute's ''[[Chronicles (magazine)|Chronicles]]''{{sfn|Kopff|2006|p=96}} and helped create another paleoconservative publication, ''[[The American Conservative]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Joiner |first=Whitney |date=September 2002 |title=Paleocons' Revenge; American Conservative L.L.C. to Launch American Conservative Magazine |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3065/is_2002_Sept_1/ai_92836524 |magazine=Folio: The Magazine for Magazine Management |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041020092305/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3065/is_2002_Sept_1/ai_92836524 |archive-date=October 20, 2004 |access-date=January 24, 2014 |via=FindArticles |deadurl=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name="The Paleo Persuasion">{{cite magazine |last=Francis |first=Samuel |author-link=Samuel T. Francis |date=December 16, 2002 |title=The Paleo Persuasion |url=http://www.amconmag.com/2002_12_16/review6.html |magazine=The American Conservative |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060329201002/http://www.amconmag.com/12_16/review6.html |archive-date=March 29, 2006 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> Paleoconservativism's concerns overlap those of the [[Old Right (United States)|Old Right]] that opposed the [[New Deal]] in the 1930s and 1940s{{sfn|Raimondo|1993}} as well as [[Social conservatism in the United States|American social conservatism]] of the late 20th century expressed, for example, in the book ''Single Issues'' by [[Joseph Sobran]]. The political theorist [[Paul Gottfried]] is credited with coining the term{{sfn|McDonald|1999|p=75}} in the 1980s.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} He says the term originally referred to various Americans, such as [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] and [[Traditionalist Catholicism|traditionalist Catholics]] and [[Agrarianism|agrarian]] [[Southern United States|Southerners]], who turned to [[anti-communism]] during the [[Cold War]].{{sfn|Gottfried|2006}}

==Core beliefs==

===Name===
The prefix "paleo" derives from the [[Greek language|Greek]] root ''[[wikt:paleo-|παλαιός]]'', meaning "ancient" or "old". It is somewhat [[:wikt:tongue-in-cheek|tongue-in-cheek]] and refers to the paleoconservatives' claim to represent a more historic, authentic conservative tradition than that found in [[neoconservatism]]. Adherents of paleoconservatism often describe themselves simply as "paleo". Neoconservative [[Rich Lowry]] of ''[[National Review]]'' claims the prefix "is designed to obscure the fact that it is a recent ideological creation of post–Cold War politics".<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lowry |first=Richard |author-link=Rich Lowry |year=2005 |title=Reaganism v. Neo-Reaganism |url=http://nationalinterest.org/article/reaganism-v-neo-reaganism-432 |url-access=subscription |magazine=The National Interest |issue=79 |publisher=Center for the National Interest |pages=35–41 |issn=1938-1573 |jstor=42897547 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref>

The paleoconservatives use the term "[[conservatism|conservative]]" somewhat differently from some American opponents of [[Left-wing politics|leftism]]. Paleoconservatives may reject attempts by [[Rush Limbaugh]] and others to graft short-term policy goals—such as [[school choice]], [[enterprise zone]] and [[faith-based initiatives]]—into the core of conservatism. This is mainly due to the paleoconservatives' desire to see these incorporated as long-term institutional goals, rather than short-term victories for the movement itself. In this way, paleoconservatives are generally regarded as taking the "long view" toward [[American conservatism]], willing to suffer temporary setbacks while never taking their aim off the goal of establishing the primacy of conservative thought into [[Politics of the United States|American politics]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Limbaugh |first=Rush |author-link=Rush Limbaugh |date=October 17, 2005 |title=Holding Court |url=http://www.opinionjournal.com/ac/?id=110007417 |work=Wall Street Journal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100111043433/http://www.opinionjournal.com/ac/?id=110007417 |archive-date=January 11, 2010 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref>

Moreover, [[Samuel T. Francis]], [[Thomas Fleming (political writer)|Thomas Fleming]] and some other paleoconservatives de-emphasized the "conservative" part of the "paleoconservative" label, saying that they do not want the ''status quo'' preserved.{{sfn|Francis|1994}}<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Foer |first=Franklin |author-link=Franklin Foer |date=July 22, 2002 |title=Home Bound |url=http://www.tnr.com/article/home-bound |magazine=The New Republic |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091001193300/http://www.tnr.com/article/home-bound |archive-date=October 1, 2009 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> Fleming and [[Paul Gottfried]] called such thinking "stupid tenacity" and described it as "a series of trenches dug in defense of last year's revolution".{{sfn|Gottfried|Fleming|1988|p=xv}} Francis defined authentic conservatism as "the survival and enhancement of a particular people and its institutionalized cultural expressions".<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Francis |first=Samuel |author-link=Samuel T. Francis |date=July 1992 |title=The Buchanan Revolution |url=http://www.samfrancis.net/pdf/all1992.pdf |magazine=Chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040723154821/http://www.samfrancis.net/pdf/all1992.pdf |archive-date=July 23, 2004 |access-date=January 27, 2018 |via=SamFrancis.net}}</ref> He said of the paleoconservative movement: {{quote|What paleoconservatism tries to tell Americans is that the dominant forces in their society are no longer committed to conserving the traditions, institutions, and values that created and formed it, and, therefore, that those who are really conservative in any serious sense and wish to live under those traditions, institutions, and values need to oppose the dominant forces and form new ones.<ref name="(Con)fusion on the Right">{{cite magazine |last=Francis |first=Samuel |author-link=Samuel T. Francis |date=March 2004 |title=(Con)fusion on the Right |url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/March2004/0304Principalities.html |magazine=Chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070404042145/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/March2004/0304Principalities.html |archive-date=April 4, 2007 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref>}}

The earliest mention of the word "paleoconservative" listed in [[LexisNexis|Nexis]]<ref>Search conducted September 8, 2006.</ref>{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} is an article by [[J. Patrick Lewis]] in the October 20, 1984 issue of ''[[The Nation]]'', referring to academic economists who allegedly work to redefine poverty.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lewis |first=J. Patrick |author-link=J. Patrick Lewis |date=October 20, 1984 |title=Willing Goodness |magazine=The Nation}}</ref> The fourth edition of the ''[[American Heritage Dictionary]]'' lists a generic, informal use of the term, meaning "extremely or stubbornly conservative in political matters". Outside of the United States, the word is sometimes spelled "palaeoconservative".<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Reid |first=Stuart |author-link=Stuart Reid (English journalist) |date=May 31, 2003 |title=Diary |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2003/05/diary-394/ |url-access=limited |magazine=The Spectator |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref>

===Conservative heritage===
Many paleoconservatives identify themselves as [[Traditionalist conservatism in the United States|classical conservatives]] and trace their philosophy to the [[Old Right (United States)|Old Right]] Republicans of the interwar period{{cn|date=December 2017}} which influenced the United States not to join the [[League of Nations]], reduce immigration with the passage of the [[Immigration Act of 1924]] and oppose [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]. They often look back even further, to [[Edmund Burke]] as well as the [[Anti-Federalism|anti-federalist]] movement that stretched from the days of [[Thomas Jefferson]] to [[John C. Calhoun]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Rockwell |first=Llewellyn H., Jr. |author-link=Lew Rockwell |date=May 2, 2002 |title=What I Learned from Paleoism |url=https://www.lewrockwell.com/2002/05/lew-rockwell/what-i-learned-from-paleoism/ |website=LewRockwell.com |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref>

Just as paleoconservatives' non-interventionism stems from their skepticism as to what extent, if any, [[Western culture]] can be transplanted or forced upon non-Western cultures, paleoconservatives' opposition to immigration is rooted in their skepticism of the ability of non-Western peoples to adopt European culture.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lubinskas |first=James|date=November 30, 2000 |title=The End of Paleoconservatism |url=http://www.frontpagemag.com/archives/politics/lubinskas11-30-00p.htm |dead-url=yes |magazine=FrontPage Magazine |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020612232153/http://www.frontpagemag.com/archives/politics/lubinskas11-30-00p.htm |archive-date=June 12, 2002 |access-date=January 24, 2014}}</ref> As a result, paleoconservatives are most distinctive in their emphatic opposition to open [[immigration]] by non-Europeans{{sfn|Machnik|2015}} and their general disapproval of United States intervention overseas.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} [[Samuel T. Francis]] wrote: {{quote|We believe that the United States derives from and is an integral part of European civilization and the European people and that the American people and government should remain [[European Americans|European in their composition and character]]. We therefore oppose the massive immigration of non-European and non-Western peoples into the United States that threatens to transform our nation into a non-European majority in our lifetime. We believe that illegal immigration must be stopped, if necessary by military force and placing troops on our national borders; that illegal aliens must be returned to their own countries; and that legal immigration must be severely restricted or halted through appropriate changes in our laws and policies.<ref>{{cite web |last=Francis |first=Sam |author-link=Samuel T. Francis |title=Statement of Principles |url=http://cofcc.org/introduction/statement-of-principles/ |publisher=Council of Conservative Citizens |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703020712/http://cofcc.org/introduction/statement-of-principles/ |archive-date=July 3, 2013 |access-date=January 27, 2018 |deadurl=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref>}}

They are also strongly critical of [[neoconservatives]] and their sympathizers in print media, talk radio and cable TV news.<ref name="libe193-20021007-06.html">{{cite web |last=Tuma |first=Kevin |year=2002 |title=The Myth of GOP Conservatism: The Ugly Truth about the Republican Party |url=http://www.ncc-1776.org/tle2002/libe193-20021007-06.html |website=The Libertarian Enterprise |issue=193 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> Paleoconservatives often say they are not conservatives in the sense that they necessarily wish to preserve existing institutions or seek merely to slow the growth of modern big-government conservatism.<ref>{{cite web |last=Larison |first=Daniel |title=How Paleo and Fusionist Conservatism Differ |url=http://acuf.org/issues/issue3/040107med.asp |publisher=American Conservative Union Foundation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040205201328/http://acuf.org/issues/issue3/040107med.asp |archive-date=February 5, 2004 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> They do not wish to be closely identified with the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].<ref name="libe193-20021007-06.html"/> Rather, they seek the renewal of "small 'r'" republican society in the context of the Western heritage, customs and civilization.<ref>{{cite web |title=Conservativism, Chronicles and Paleoconservativism |url=http://acuf.org/issues/issue2/chronicles.asp |publisher=American Conservative Union Foundation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050422081821/http://acuf.org/issues/issue2/chronicles.asp |archive-date=April 22, 2005 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> Author Joseph Scotchie wrote: {{quote|Republics mind their own business. Their governments have very limited powers, and their people are too busy practicing self-government to worry about problems in other countries. Empires not only bully smaller, defenseless nations, they also can't leave their own, hapless subjects alone{{sfn|Scotchie|2004|p=85}} ... Empires and small government aren't compatible, either.<ref name="The Paleo Persuasion"/>}}

By contrast, paleoconservatives see neoconservatives as [[empire]]-builders and themselves as defenders of the republic, pointing to [[Roman Empire|Rome]] as an example of how an ongoing campaign of military [[expansionism]] can destroy a republic.<ref>{{cite news |last=Judis |first=John B. |author-link=John Judis |date=October 3, 1999 |title=The Buchanan Doctrine |url= https://www.nytimes.com/books/99/10/03/reviews/991003.03judist.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref>

On some issues, many paleoconservatives are hard to distinguish from others on the conservative spectrum. For example, they tend to oppose [[abortion]] on demand{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} and [[gay marriage]]<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Chu |first=Jeff |date=August 20, 2006 |title=10 Questions for Pat Buchanan |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1229098-1,00.html |magazine=Time |location=New York |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930190049/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1229098-1,00.html |archive-date=September 30, 2007 |access-date=May 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Fleming |first=Thomas |author-link=Thomas Fleming (political writer) |date=September 8, 2005 |title=Ethics 01A.1: Gay Marriage, Democracy |url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Ethics_01A___Gay_Ma.writeback |dead-url=yes |magazine=Chronicles |location=Rockford, Illinois |publisher=Rockford Institute |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927173854/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Ethics_01A___Gay_Ma.writeback |archive-date=September 27, 2006 |access-date=August 27, 2006}}</ref> while supporting [[handgun]] ownership<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Francis |first=Samuel |author-link=Samuel T. Francis |date=October 15, 2003 |title=Gun Control: The Final Blow |url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/News/Francis/NewsSF101503.html |dead-url=yes |magazine=Chronicle |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050313154240/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/News/Francis/NewsSF101503.html |archive-date=March 13, 2005 |access-date=September 1, 2006}}</ref> and an [[original intent]] reading of the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Sobran |first=Joseph |author-link=Joseph Sobran |title=How Tyranny Came to America |url=http://www.fightthebias.com/Resources/Rec_Read/how_tyranny_came_to_america.htm |website=FightTheBias.com |access-date=January 24, 2014}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=January 2018}} On the other hand, paleoconservatives are often more sympathetic to [[environmental protection]],<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Versluis |first=Arthur |author-link=Arthur Versluis |date=May 5, 2003 |title=Strip Malls Across the Fruited Plain |url=http://www.amconmag.com/05_05_03/article2.html |magazine=The American Conservative |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108182512/http://www.amconmag.com/article/2003/may/05/00018/ |archive-date=January 8, 2009 |access-date=January 24, 2014}}</ref>{{verification failed|date=January 2018}} [[animal welfare]]<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Scully |first=Matthew |author-link=Matthew Scully |date=May 23, 2005 |title=Fear Factories |url=http://www.amconmag.com/2005_05_23/cover.html |magazine=The American Conservative |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227210149/http://www.amconmag.com/article/2005/may/23/00007/ |archive-date=December 27, 2008 |access-date=January 24, 2014}}</ref>{{verification failed|date=January 2018}} and [[anti-consumerism]]<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Richert |first=Scott P. |date=December 2003 |title=Always Dead Downtowns. Always |url=http://chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/December2003/1203Rockford.html |dead-url=yes |magazine=Chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821025204/http://chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/December2003/1203Rockford.html |archive-date=August 21, 2006 |access-date=September 17, 2006}}</ref>{{verification failed|date=January 2018}} than others on the American right-wing.

===Human nature, tradition and reason===
Paleoconservatives argue that since [[human nature]] is limited and finite, any attempt to create a man-made [[utopia]] is headed for disaster and potential carnage. Instead, they lean toward tradition, family, customs, religious institutions and classical learning to provide wisdom and guidance.<ref>{{cite web |last=Peppe |first=Enrico |date=April 27, 2004 |title=Thomas Molnar: The Counter-Revolution |url=http://www.intellectualconservative.com/article3366.html |website=IntellectualConservative.com |access-date=January 24, 2014}}</ref>

Fleming stated this opposition to abstract ideals in a way that critic [[David Brooks (cultural commentator)|David Brooks]] called a "startling crescendo":
{{quote|Among the most dangerous of our theoretical illusions are the political fantasies that can be summed up in words like democracy; equality, and natural rights; the principle of one man, one vote and the American tradition of self-government. No one who lives in the world with his eyes open can actually believe in any of this.<ref name="Buchananism">{{cite news| title=Buchananism: An Intellectual Cause| first=David| last=Brooks |author-link=David Brooks (cultural commentator) | work=The Weekly Standard| date=11 March 1996}}</ref>}}

The political scientist [[W. Wesley McDonald]] explains the opposition to [[ideology]]{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} this way:
{{quote|In a humane social order, a community of spirit is fostered in which generations are bound together. According to [Russell] Kirk, this link is achieved through moral and social norms that transcend the particularities of time and place and, because they form the basis of genuine civilized existence, can only be neglected at great peril. These norms, reflected in religious dogmas, traditions, humane letters, social habit and custom, and prescriptive institutions, create the sources of the true community that is the final end of politics.<ref>{{cite web |title=Russell Kirk and the Age of Ideology by W. Wesley McDonald |url=http://www.umsystem.edu/upress/spring2004/mcdonald.htm |publisher=University of Missouri Press |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060105180429/http://www.umsystem.edu/upress/spring2004/mcdonald.htm |archive-date=January 5, 2006 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref>}}

Along these lines, [[Joseph Sobran]] argues in his ''Pensees'' that [[Western civilization]] relies on civility at the center of the society:
{{quote|Civility is the relationship among citizens in a republic. It corresponds to the condition we call "freedom," which is not just an absence of restraint or coercion, but the security of living under commonly recognized rules of conduct. Not all these rules are enforced by the state; legal institutions of civility depend on the ethical substratum and collapse when it is absent. And in fact the colloquial sense of civility as good manners is relevant to its political meaning: citizens typically deal with each other by consent, and they have to say "please" and "thank you" to each other.<ref name="f_pensees.htm">{{cite magazine |last=Sobran |first=Joseph |author-link=Joseph Sobran |year=1985 |title=''Pensees'': Notes for the Reactionary of Tomorrow |magazine=National Review |volume=37 |issue=25 |location=New York |page=28 |issn=0028-0038}}</ref>}}

Certain paleoconservatives say that tradition is a better guide than reason. For example, [[Mel Bradford]] wrote that certain questions are settled before any serious deliberation concerning a preferred course of conduct may begin. This ethic is based in a "culture of families, linked by friendship, common enemies, and common projects".<ref>{{cite book |last=Bradford |first=M.&nbsp;E. |author-link=Mel Bradford |year=1990
|title=The Reactionary Imperative: Essays Literary and Political |location=Peru, Illinois |publisher=Sherwood Sugden |page=129}} Quoted in {{harvnb|Murphy|2001|p=233}}.</ref> So a good conservative keeps "a clear sense of what Southern grandmothers have always meant in admonishing children, 'we don't do that'".<ref>{{cite book |last=Bradford |first=M.&nbsp;E. |author-link=Mel Bradford |year=1990
|title=The Reactionary Imperative: Essays Literary and Political |location=Peru, Illinois |publisher=Sherwood Sugden |pages=119, 121}} Quoted in {{harvnb|Murphy|2001|p=233}}.</ref>

Fleming calls tradition "a body of wisdom and truth and a set of attitudes and behavior handed down from one generation to another. It is our parents' respect for their grandfathers that we reflect when we refuse to think ourselves wiser than our ancestors and do not presume to condemn their shortcomings".{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} By following tradition, Sobran said that society can maintain continuity with the past through words, rituals, records, commemorations and laws: {{quote|There is no question of "resisting change." The only question is what can and should be salvaged from "devouring time." Conservation is a labor, not indolence, and it takes discrimination to identify and save a few strands of tradition in the incessant flow of mutability. In fact conservation is so hard that it could never be achieved by sheer conscious effort. Most of it has to be done by habit, as when we speak in such a way as to make ourselves understood by others without their having to consult a dictionary, and thereby give a little permanence to the kind of tradition that is a language.<ref name="f_pensees.htm"/>}}

Furthermore, James Kalb argues that tradition succeeds where ideology fails because it includes habits and attitudes about things that are hard to articulate rationally. Many aspects of social life resist clear definition, so technocratic approaches to social policy deserve suspicion: {{quote|Our knowledge is partial and attained with difficulty. The effects of political proposals are difficult to predict and as the proposals become more ambitious their effects become incalculable. We can't evaluate political ideas without accepting far more beliefs, presumptions and attitudes than we could possibly judge critically.<ref name="FAQ">{{cite web |last=Kalb |first=Jim |title=Jim Kalb's Conservatism FAQ |url=http://homepages.cs.ncl.ac.uk/chris.holt/home.informal/lounge/politics/conservativism/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060629205328/http://homepages.cs.ncl.ac.uk/chris.holt/home.informal/lounge/politics/conservativism/ |archive-date=June 29, 2006 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref>}}

===Concrete roots===
{{citation needed span |date=January 2018 |text=Many paleoconservatives also say}} that Westerners have lost touch with their classical and European heritage, to the point that they are in danger of losing their civilization.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Fleming |first=Thomas |author-link=Thomas Fleming (political writer) |date=January 28, 2006 |title=Back to Mordor |url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Back_to_Mordor.html?seemore%3Dy |dead-url=yes |magazine=Chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927172125/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Back_to_Mordor.html?seemore=y |archive-date=September 27, 2006 |access-date=August 26, 2006}}</ref> Fleming wrote:

{{quote|The decadence of a civilization by loss of faith and vigour can be observed more than once in history. What is extraordinary about the American situation is the stupidity. The Romans, such is my impression, did not become stupid and incompetent with their decadence. Americans have not lost faith in their cultural inheritance—they have been entirely separated from it. How this happened is one of the few topics still worth exploring in this Twilight.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fleming |first=Thomas |author-link=Thomas Fleming (political writer) |date=May 25, 2006 |title=Da Vinci Code Protest |url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Da_Vinci_Code_Prote.writeback |deadurl=yes |website=Chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927171625/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Da_Vinci_Code_Prote.writeback |archive-date=September 27, 2006 |access-date=September 23, 2006}}</ref>}}

Paleoconservatives tend to dislike abstract principles presented without connection to concrete roots, like religion, heritage, or traditional institutions. This distaste for [[universalism]] includes the doctrinal conclusions by [[Socialism|socialists]], [[Neo-scholasticism|neo-Thomists]] and [[Straussians]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} For example, Bradford wrote in ''A Better Guide Than Reason'' (citing [[Michael Oakeshott]]): {{quote|The only freedom which can last is a freedom embodied somewhere, rooted in a history, located in space, sanctioned by genealogy, and blessed by a religious establishment. The only equality which abstract rights, insisted upon outside the context of politics, are likely to provide is the equality of universal slavery. It is a lesson which Western man is only now beginning to learn.{{sfn|Bradford|1994|p=xviii}}}}

Some paleoconservatives also profess a conservative value-centered [[historicism]],{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} which Gottfried defines as "the belief that historical circumstances set values".<ref name="The Real Cabal">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/September2003/0903Francis.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-09-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060106021320/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/September2003/0903Francis.html |archivedate=January 6, 2006 |df= }}</ref> This is distinguished from [[nihilism]], [[postmodernism]], and [[moral relativism]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} Francis argued that this position is a "Burkean appeal to tradition".<ref name="The Real Cabal"/> For example, [[Edmund Burke]] wrote in his ''[[Reflections on the Revolution in France]]'':
{{quote|I cannot stand forward, and give praise or blame to anything which relates to human actions, and human concerns, on a simple view of the object, as it stands stripped of every relation, in all the nakedness and solitude of metaphysical abstraction. Circumstances (which with some gentlemen pass for nothing) give in reality to every political principle its distinguishing colour and discriminating effect. The circumstances are what render every civil and political scheme beneficial or noxious to mankind.{{sfn|Burke|1790|pp=7–8}}}}

[[Claes G. Ryn]] says that life has "an enduring purpose, but one that manifests itself differently as individuals and circumstances are different".{{sfn|Ryn|1998|p=90}} He writes: {{quote|For the conservative, the universal imperative that binds human beings does not announce its purpose in simple, declaratory statements. How, then, does one discern its demands? Sometimes only with difficulty. Only through effort can the good or true or beautiful be discovered, and they must be realized differently in different historical circumstances. The same universal values have diverse manifestations. Some of the concrete instantiations of universality take us by surprise. Because there is no simple roadmap to good, human beings need freedom and imagination to find it. Universality has nothing to do with uniformity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/orig5/ryn2.html |title=Where in the World Are We Going? by Claes G. Ryn |publisher=Lewrockwell.com |date=April 2, 2006 |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>}}

===Anti-federalism===
{{seealso|New Federalism}}
Anti-federalism (see the [[Anti-Federalism|American anti-Federalist movement]]) is another key aspect of paleoconservatism, which adherents see as an antitype to the [[managerial state]]. The paleoconservative flavor urges honoring the principle of [[subsidiarity]], that is decentralized government, local rule, private property and minimal bureaucracy.<ref name="FAQ"/> In an international context, this view would be known as [[federalism]] and paleoconservatives often look to [[John C. Calhoun]] for inspiration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/young-andrew/young-andrew11.html |title=Rescuing Calhoun by Andrew Young |publisher=Lewrockwell.com |date=July 30, 2005 |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> As to the role of statecraft in society, Fleming says it should not be confused with soulcraft. He gives his summary of the paleoconservative position:{{quote|Our basic position on the state has always been twofold: 1) a recognition that man is a social and political animal who cannot be treated as an "individual" without doing damage to human nature. In this sense libertarian theory is as wrong and as potentially harmful as communism. The commonwealth is therefore a natural and necessary expression of human nature that provides for the fulfillment of human needs, and 2) the modern state is a cancerous form of polity that has metastasized and poisoned the natural institutions from which the state derives all legitimacy—family, church, corporation (in the broadest sense), and neighborhood. Thus, it is almost always a mistake to try to use the modern state to accomplish moral or social ends.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Anarcho-Tyranny_Roc.writeback|title=Anarcho-Tyranny Rockford Style 
|author= Thomas Fleming |accessdate=October 7, 2006 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927173012/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Anarcho-Tyranny_Roc.writeback |archivedate=September 27, 2006 }}</ref>|sign=|source=}}For example, [[Russell Kirk]] argued that most government tasks should be performed at the local or state level. This is intended to ward off centralization and protect community sentiment by putting the decision-making power closer to the populace. He rooted this in the Christian notion of original sin as since humanity is flawed, society should not put too much power in a few hands. Gerald J. Russello concluded that this involved "a different way of thinking about government, one based on an understanding of political society as beginning in place and sentiment, which in turn supports written laws".{{sfn|Russello|2004}}

This anti-federalism extends to culture too.  In general, this means that different regional groups should be able to maintain their own distinct identity. For example, Fleming and Michael Hill argue that the American South and every other region have the right to "preserve their authentic cultural traditions and demand the same respect from others". In the Southern context, they call on citizens to "take control of their own governments, their own institutions, their own culture, their own communities and their own lives" and "wean themselves from dependence on federal largesse". They say:{{quote|A concern for states' rights, local self-government and regional identity used to be taken for granted everywhere in America. But the United States is no longer, as it once was, a federal union of diverse states and regions. National uniformity is being imposed by the political class that runs Washington, the economic class that owns Wall Street and the cultural class in charge of Hollywood and the Ivy League.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dixienet.org/rights/newdixiemanifesto.shtml |title=League of the South |website=Dixienet.org |accessdate=April 1, 2016 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>}}In a similar fashion, [[Pat Buchanan]] argued during the 1996 campaign that the social welfare should be left to the control of individual states. He also called for abolishing the [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]] and handing decision-making over to parents, teachers and districts. Controversies such as [[evolution]], [[Desegregation busing|busing]] and [[curriculum]] standards would be settled on a local basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.buchanan.org/pa-00-0725-stagnaro.html|title=Pat Buchanan on the American Future|last1=Stagnaro|first1=Carlo|date=July 24, 2000|work=The Laissez Faire City Times|accessdate=November 19, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008152646/http://www.buchanan.org/pa-00-0725-stagnaro.html|archivedate=October 8, 2008|issue=Vol 4, No 30|ref=stagnaro}}</ref> In addition, he opposed a 1998 Puerto Rican statehood plan on the grounds that the island would be ripped from its cultural and linguistic roots: "Let [[Puerto Rico]] remain Puerto Rico, and let the United States remain the United States and not try to absorb, assimilate and Americanize a people whose hearts will forever belong to that island".<ref>[http://www.buchanan.org/pa-98-0915.html "Let Puerto Rico Remain Puerto Rico", Pat Buchanan]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060826002334/http://www.buchanan.org/pa-98-0915.html|date=August 26, 2006}}</ref>

===Family===
Paleoconservatives often argue that modern managerial society is a threat to stable [[families]]. [[Allan C. Carlson]], former president of the [[Rockford Institute]], argues: {{quote|The family is the natural and fundamental [[social unit]], inscribed in our nature as human beings, rooted in marriage, rooted in the commitment to bring new life into the world, and rooted in a deep respect for both ancestors and posterity.<ref name="thc_acc_ffus.htm">{{cite web |url=http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc_acc_ffus.htm |title=THC Allan Carlson, Ph.D.: Speeches: The Howard Center |publisher=Profam.org |date=January 19, 1999 |accessdate=January 24, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515153031/http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc_acc_ffus.htm |archivedate=May 15, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>}}

He calls this a universal rule of human nature, true for Westerners and non-Westerners alike. He also argues that happiness "comes through natural family bonds" and that "the future of any nation shall be by way of the family".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc.acc.060215.korea.htm |title=THC Allan Carlson, Ph.D.: Speeches: The Howard Center |publisher=Profam.org |date=February 15, 2006 |accessdate=January 24, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515155131/http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc.acc.060215.korea.htm |archivedate=May 15, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He defines family as "a man and a woman living in a socially sanctioned bond called marriage for the purposes of propagating and rearing children, sharing intimacy and resources, and conserving lineage, property, and tradition".<ref name="thc.acc.051117.legatus.htm">{{cite web |url=http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc.acc.051117.legatus.htm |title=THC Allan Carlson, Ph.D.: Speeches: The Howard Center |publisher=Profam.org |date=November 17, 2005 |accessdate=January 24, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515135728/http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc.acc.051117.legatus.htm |archivedate=May 15, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>

{{quote| To be human is to be familial. Any significant departure from the family rooted in stable marriage, the welcoming of children, and respect for ancestors and posterity—any deviation from this social structure makes us in a way less "human": that is, I think it fair to say, the true message of modern science.<ref name="thc_acc_ffus.htm"/>}}

Sobran picks up this same theme, saying that heterosexual marriage is hard-coded into human nature: {{quote|[Even] the Pope can’t change the nature of marriage. It existed, by necessity of human nature, long before Jesus or even Abraham... This has nothing to do with mere disapproval of sodomy. Even societies that were indifferent to sodomy saw no reason to treat same-sex domestic partnerships as marriages. Why not? Because such unions don’t produce children... To put it as unromantically as possible, people who have children should be stuck with each other, sharing the responsibility.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ronald N. Neff, www.thornwalker.com |url=http://www.sobran.com/columns/2003/030805.shtml |title=Sobran Column – Is the Pope Square? |publisher=Sobran.com |date=August 5, 2003 |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>}}

Paleoconservatives also question the validity of [[gender feminism]] in similar ways, some questioning feminism in both its radical and moderate forms. They say that the push for total gender equality dehumanizes both men and women, damaging the [[nuclear family]] and sacralizing abortion. Certain attitudes toward feminism also create room for the managerial state to try engineering sexual equality. Gottfried described this position, which was influenced by scholar Allan Carlson, thus: {{quote|The change of women's role, from being primarily mothers to self-defined professionals, has been a social disaster that continues to take its toll on the family. Rather than being the culminating point of Western Christian gentility, the movement of women into commerce and politics may be seen as exactly the opposite, the descent by increasingly disconnected individuals into social chaos.<ref name="gottfried051702.htm">{{cite web| url=https://www.lewrockwell.com/2001/04/paul-gottfried/the-trouble-with-feminism/| title=The Trouble with Feminism| first=Paul| last= Gottfried}}</ref>}}

====Post-family order====
[[Allan C. Carlson]] says that we live in a "post-family order", in which elites no longer accept the centrality of family life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc_acc_wcfregdc_0111.htm |title=THC Allan Carlson, Ph.D.: Speeches: The Howard Center |publisher=Profam.org |date=October 26, 2001 |accessdate=January 24, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827174809/http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc_acc_wcfregdc_0111.htm |archivedate=August 27, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Ethics_O1A2__Gay_M.writeback|title=Ethics O1A.2: Gay Marriage 
|author=Thomas Fleming |accessdate=September 14, 2006 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927172313/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Ethics_O1A2__Gay_M.writeback |archivedate=September 27, 2006 }}</ref> In response, he calls for a pro-active social conservatism that seeks "real alternatives to the centralized ‘corporate state’ that are compatible with liberty and family life". He argues that there is a permanent tension between the family and "individualist, industrialized society".<ref name="thc_acc_dectnf.htm">{{cite web|url=http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc_acc_dectnf.htm |title=THC Allan Carlson, Ph.D.: Speeches: The Howard Center |publisher=Profam.org |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120911035252/http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc_acc_dectnf.htm |archivedate=September 11, 2012 |df= }}</ref> He says the modern "abstract state" too often sees the family as "its principal rival" and tries to suppress it. It can also hurt family living by the [[unintended consequences]] of public policy with good intentions.<ref name="thc_acc_dectnf.htm"/> He also chides American Republicans "for consistently favoring Wall Street over Main Street".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.profam.org/press/thc.pr.060320.htm |title=THC: The Howard Center: Press Release |publisher=Profam.org |date=May 13, 2007 |accessdate=January 24, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201181329/http://profam.org/press/thc.pr.060320.htm |archivedate=February 1, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>

As an alternative to the "abstract state", Carlson argues the state must recognize that men and women "are different in reproductive, economic, and social functions", even though they share political and property rights.<ref name="thc.acc.051117.legatus.htm"/> He says that churches and other religious bodies must step in and help rebuild "family-centered communities".<ref name="thc_acc_dectnf.htm"/> As for common people, he says: {{quote|Men and women are both called home to rebuild families with an inner sanctity, to relearn the authentic meanings of the ancient words husbandry and housewifery, and to exercise the natural family functions of education, the care of the weak, charity, and a common economic life.<ref name="thc_acc_dectnf.htm"/>}}

Carlson argues that the family's greatest challenge in the early 21st century comes from what he calls "soft [[totalitarianism]]s", which are "packaged around a militant secular individualism, but still seeking to build a marriage-free, post-family order".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc_acc_frc_sfl_040616.htm |title=THC Allan Carlson, Ph.D.: Speeches: The Howard Center |publisher=Profam.org |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515145035/http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc_acc_frc_sfl_040616.htm |archivedate=May 15, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  This includes same-sex marriage, the left's association of family values with [[abortion]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc.acc.060211.econ.abort.htm |title=THC Allan Carlson, Ph.D.: Speeches: The Howard Center |publisher=Profam.org |date=February 11, 2006 |accessdate=January 24, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515141532/http://www.profam.org/docs/acc/thc.acc.060211.econ.abort.htm |archivedate=May 15, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and "[[equity feminism]]".<ref name="thc.acc.051117.legatus.htm"/> Francis uses similar ideas to argue that society should regulate sexual behavior, specifically laws against sodomy and gays in the military.<ref>"Sex and consequences", ''The Washington Times'', February 2, 1993.</ref>

==Polemics==
Other contemporary luminaries include [[Donald Livingston]], a Professor of Philosophy at Emory{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} and corresponding editor for [[Chronicles (magazine)|''Chronicles'']];<ref name="Yr2006">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/magazine.cgi/Yr%202006/August/Contents.html?seemore=y |publisher=Chronicles Magazine |title=Contents |accessdate=November 5, 2006 |date=August 2006 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061012062455/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/magazine.cgi/Yr%202006/August/Contents.html?seemore=y |archivedate=October 12, 2006 }}</ref> [[Paul Craig Roberts]], an attorney and former [[Reagan administration]] [[US Treasury Department|Treasury]] official; [[Joseph Sobran]], a columnist and contributing editor for ''Chronicles'';<ref name="Yr2006"/> the novelist and essayist [[Chilton Williamson]], senior editor for books at ''Chronicles'';<ref name="Yr2006"/> and the historian [[Clyde N. Wilson]], long-time contributing editor for ''Chronicles''.<ref name="Yr2006"/> Another prominent paleoconservative, [[Theodore Pappas]],{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} is the current executive editor of ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.britannica.com/press/releases/new_site.html |title=Redesigned Britannica Site Serves Enjoyment with Enlightenment |date=December 8, 2005 |accessdate=November 3, 2006 |publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061111124535/http://corporate.britannica.com/press/releases/new_site.html |archivedate=November 11, 2006 }} – EB corporate site mentioning Pappas</ref>

The movement combines disparate people and ideas that might seem incompatible in another context.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.etherzone.com/2003/wilk020603.shtml| title=Voices in The Wilderness| first=David| last= Wilkinson}}</ref> Such diversity of thought echoes the paleo opposition to [[ideology]] and political [[rationalism]], reflecting the influence of thinkers like [[Russell Kirk]]<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/July2004/0704Richert.html |date=July 2004 |journal=Chronicles |title=Review: Russell Kirk and the Negation of Ideology |first=Scott P. |last=Richert |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403225741/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/July2004/0704Richert.html |archivedate=April 3, 2007 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> and [[Michael Oakeshott]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Patrick West |url=http://www.spiked-online.com/Articles/0000000CAD9C.htm |title=The Poverty of Multiculturalism |publisher=Spiked-online.com |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>

[[Pat Buchanan]] argues that a good politician must "defend the moral order rooted in the [[Old Testament|Old]] and [[New Testament]] and [[Natural Law]]"—and that "the deepest problems in our society are not economic or political, but moral".<ref name="pma-00-0621-fulani.html">[http://www.buchanan.org/pma-00-0621-fulani.html Pat Buchanan Responds To Lenora Fulani'S Resignation – Buchanan Campaign Press Releases – theinternetbrigade – Official Web Site]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061005164216/http://www.buchanan.org/pma-00-0621-fulani.html |date=October 5, 2006 }}</ref> On the other hand, Samuel T. Francis complained that the [[Christian right]] focuses on certain social issues and neglects other civilizational crises.<ref name="all1994.pdf">{{cite web|url=http://www.samfrancis.net/pdf/all1994.pdf |title=samfrancis.net |publisher=samfrancis.net |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>

===Kirkian legacy===
[[Russell Kirk]] (1914–1994) is a key figure in paleoconservatism, in that several of his books present an outline of a pervasive Anglo-American conservative tradition that exists despite many other distinctions. His own career stretched long enough to for him to defend [[Robert A. Taft]] in the 1950s, write for ''[[National Review]]'' during the Cold War, criticize neoconservatism in the 1980s and give speeches supporting Buchanan in 1992. One neoconservative writer, Dan Himmelfarb, even refers to Kirk's ''The Conservative Mind'' as "the seminal work of paleoconservatism", even though it was first published in 1953.<ref>{{cite web|last=Abrams |first=Elliott |url=http://www.commentarymagazine.com/Summaries/V85I5P56-1.htm |title=Time For Obama To Embarrass His Own VP? |publisher=Commentarymagazine.com |date=September 22, 2008 |accessdate=January 24, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050420233102/http://www.commentarymagazine.com/Summaries/V85I5P56-1.htm |archivedate=April 20, 2005 |df= }}</ref>

Kirk developed six "canons" of conservatism.{{sfn|Kirk|1986|pp=8–9}} Gerald J. Russello described them thus:
{{quote|(1) a belief in a transcendent order, which Kirk described variously as based in tradition, divine revelation, or natural law; (2) an affection for the "variety and mystery" of human existence; (3) a conviction that society requires orders and classes that emphasize "natural distinctions;" (4) a belief that property and freedom are closely linked; (5) a faith in custom, convention and prescription; and (6) a recognition that innovation must be tied to existing traditions and customs, which is a respect for the political value of prudence.{{sfn|Russello|2004|p=109}}}}

In addition, Kirk said that "all culture arises out of religion. When religious faith decays, culture must decline, though often seeming to flourish for a space after the religion which has nourished it has sunk into disbelief".{{sfn|Kirk|2014}}

Kirk called [[libertarianism|libertarians]] "chirping sectaries" by quoting [[T. S. Eliot|T.&nbsp;S. Eliot]] and said that they and conservatives have nothing in common apart from their opposition to [[collectivism]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Kirk |first=Russell |author-link=Russell Kirk |year=1981 |title=Libertarians: Chirping Sectaries |url=https://isistatic.org/journal-archive/ma/25_04/kirk.pdf |journal=Modern Age |volume=25 |issue=4 |pages=345, 349 |access-date=January 26, 2018}}</ref> He called the movement "an ideological clique forever splitting into sects still smaller and odder, but rarely conjugating".<ref name="Kirk 1981, p. 349">{{cite magazine |last=Kirk |first=Russell |author-link=Russell Kirk |year=1981 |title=Libertarians: Chirping Sectaries |url=https://isistatic.org/journal-archive/ma/25_04/kirk.pdf |journal=Modern Age |volume=25 |issue=4 |page=349 |access-date=January 26, 2018}}</ref> He said a line of division exists between believers in "some sort of transcendent moral order" and "utilitarians admitting no transcendent sanctions for conduct", libertarians being in the latter category.<ref name="Kirk 1981, p. 349"/>

Kirk also popularized the Anglo-Irish statesman [[Edmund Burke]] as the prototypical conservative—and many paleoconservatives consider him a hallowed ancestor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/January2001/0101RoundTable.htm |title=Law, Morality, and Religion |first=Stephen B. |last=Presser |publisher=Chronicles Magazine |year=2001 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070404042403/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/January2001/0101RoundTable.htm |archivedate=April 4, 2007 }}</ref> For them, he represents a vital link between the American right and the greater tradition of British customs and [[common law]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://users.etown.edu/m/mcdonaldw/Kirkbc.htm| title=Russell Kirk's Conservative Mind| first=W. Wesley| last=McDonald| authorlink=W. Wesley McDonald| deadurl=yes| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920021720/http://users.etown.edu/m/mcdonaldw/Kirkbc.htm| archivedate=September 20, 2013| df=mdy-all}}</ref>{{verification failed|date=January 2018}} As such, his ideas are a touchstone for a conservatism that respects tradition, while rejecting [[authoritarianism]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}

Unlike paleoconservatives, Kirk was not particularly influenced by the social sciences and other "modernist disciplines".{{sfn|McDonald|2004|p=216}}

===Precursors===
In the United States, the [[Southern Agrarians]],{{sfn|Murphy|2001|p=254}} [[John T. Flynn]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/stromberg/stromberg23.html| title= War, Peace, and the State| first= Joseph|last=Stromberg}}</ref> [[Albert Jay Nock]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/mcmaken/mcmaken75.html| title= The Helpful Persuasion| first= Ryan| last= McMaken}}</ref> [[Garet Garrett]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.antiwar.com/orig/anti-imp2.html| title= Garet Garrett: Exemplar of the Old Right| first=Justin| last=Raimondo| authorlink=Justin Raimondo}}</ref> [[Robert R. McCormick]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/rothbard/rothbard45.html| title=Life in the Old Right| first= Murray N.| last= Rothbard}}</ref> [[Felix Morley]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.antiwar.com/stromberg/s120799.html| title= Felix Morley: An Old-fashioned Republican| first= Joseph R.| last= Stromberg}}</ref> and [[Richard M. Weaver]],{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} among others, articulated positions that have influenced contemporary paleoconservatives. Some paleoconservatives embrace the decentralizing tenets of the [[Anti-Federalists]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/rockwell/down-presidency.html| title= Down With the Presidency| first= Llewellyn H., Jr.| last= Rockwell}}</ref> such as [[John Dickinson (delegate)|John Dickinson]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/orig5/galles5.html| title= John Dickenson, Founder and Revolutionary| first= Gary| last= Galles}}</ref> and [[George Mason]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/dilorenzo/dilorenzo90.html| title= Standard Weekly Lies| first= Thomas J.| last= DiLorenzo}}</ref> Neoconservative critic [[David Brooks (journalist)|David Brooks]] lists [[William Jennings Bryan]], T.&nbsp;S. Eliot, [[Allen Tate]], [[John Crowe Ransom]], [[Cleanth Brooks]] and [[Walker Percy]] as major paleo influences.<ref name="Buchananism"/>

Counter-revolutionary (Roman Catholic) European precursors to the paleoconservatives include [[Joseph de Maistre]], [[Charles Maurras]], [[Juan Donoso Cortés]], [[Klemens Wenzel von Metternich]] and [[Pope Pius IX]], specifically in the [[Roman Catholic]] traditionalist subset of paleoconservatism. [[G. K. Chesterton|G.&nbsp;K. Chesterton]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theenglandproject.net/documents/secret-people.html |title=The England Project |accessdate=2016-02-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090714122918/http://www.theenglandproject.net/documents/secret-people.html |archivedate=July 14, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>{{verification failed|date=January 2018}}<ref>See ISI's scholarly analysis of him in ''Modern Age'' and ''Intercollegiate Review''</ref> and [[Hilaire Belloc]] also influence paleo thought.{{cn|date=September 2017}} Regarding Chesterton and Belloc, Sobran said:
{{quote|This new, paganized Western society under the comprehensive state would have come as much less of a surprise to us if we'd paid more attention to the two great English Catholic writers of the pre-Bolshevik period. Hilaire Belloc and G.K. Chesterton saw it coming.

In 1912, Belloc predicted the rise of a new form of tyranny, which he called "the Servile State," neither capitalist nor socialist, in which one part of the population would be forced to support the other. He was not always accurate in detail, but he was right in principle. He saw that the cellular structure of Christian society was under assault.

Chesterton agreed. Together both men resisted modernity in religion, morality, politics, economics, and art. They celebrated the Middle Ages, small private property, and above all Catholicism. In a famous epigram, typically defiant in its simplicity, Belloc proclaimed: "Europe is the Faith, and the Faith is Europe."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secondspring.co.uk/articles/sobran.htm |title=sobran |publisher=Secondspring.co.uk |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>}}

Other historical sources referenced by paleoconservatives include [[Niccolò Machiavelli]], [[Thomas Hobbes]] and [[Antonio Gramsci]].{{sfn|McDonald|1999|p=75}} Contrarian leftists such as [[Eugene Genovese]], [[Christopher Lasch]] and [[Paul Piccone]] have also influenced the movement.{{sfn|Gottfried|1993|p=154}} Modern European continental conservatives [[Jacques Barzun]], [[Alain de Benoist]] and [[René Girard]] have also been praised by paleoconservatives.{{cn|date=December 2017}}

===Southern tradition===
Paul V. Murphy wrote that they developed "a particularistic politics of [[states' rights]] and [[Localism (politics)|localism]], which they combine with a cultural and social criticism defined by Christian and patriarchal [[organicism]]".{{sfn|Murphy|2001|p=218}} He also says the Southern traditionalist worldview evolved into what appeared in ''Chronicles'' from the mid-1980s onward, a focus on national identity mixed with regional particularity, plus skepticism of abstract theory and centralized power. They also said the mainstream view of the old South was distorted. For example, Bradford said: {{quote|The way to look at the institution of slavery is not backward from 1991 but forward from the hundred years before 1860. Slavery was like the rising and setting of the sun, a fixture of life. In pre-Colonial times, everyone was racist, except a few [[Quakers]]. Jefferson thought that Negroes were not capable of taking care of themselves, that they were somewhere between helpless children and orangutans.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Cartwright |first=Gary |date=March 1992 |title=Mr. Right |url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/mag/issues/1992-03-01/academia.php |magazine=Texas Monthly |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930023810/http://www.texasmonthly.com/mag/issues/1992-03-01/academia.php |archive-date=September 30, 2007 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref>}}

In the 1995 "New Dixie Manifesto", Thomas Fleming and Michael Hill argued that Southerners are pelted with ethnic slurs, denied self-government and stripped of their symbols, including the [[Confederate flag]].<ref>[http://www.leagueofthesouth.net/static/homepage/intro_articles/newdixiemanifesto.html leagueofthesouth.net] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926233755/http://www.leagueofthesouth.net/static/homepage/intro_articles/newdixiemanifesto.html |date=September 26, 2007 }}</ref> They wrote,
{{quote|After so many decades of strife, black and white Southerners of good will should be left alone to work out their destinies, avoiding, before it is too late, the urban hell that has been created by the lawyers, social engineers and imperial bureaucrats who have grown rich on programs that have done nothing to help anyone but themselves.}}

[[Thomas DiLorenzo]] revisited the Southern paleo critique of [[Abraham Lincoln]] in his book ''[[The Real Lincoln]]''. He gives it a [[paleolibertarian]] twist, saying the president followed [[mercantilism]], [[protectionism]] and the example of [[Alexander Hamilton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/dilorenzo/dilorenzo94.html |title=Getting Lincoln Half Right and Half Wrong by Thomas DiLorenzo |publisher=Lewrockwell.com |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> He also said that the [[United States Civil War|Civil War]] was about destroying the right of [[secession]], not freeing slaves.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} Furthermore, he claims that the praise Lincoln commonly receives from conservatives is misguided: {{quote|The Gettysburg Address was brilliant oratory, but it was also political subterfuge. As [[H. L. Mencken|H.&nbsp;L. Mencken]] pointed out, it was the Southerners who were fighting for the [[consent of the governed]] and it was Lincoln's government that opposed them. They no longer consented to being governed by Washington, D.C.  Lincoln's admonition that government "of the people, by the people, for the people" would perish from the earth if the right of secession were sustained was equally absurd. The United States remained a democracy, and the Confederate States of America would have been a democratic country as well.  Lincoln's notion that secession would "destroy" the government of the United States is also bizarre in light of the fact that after secession took place the US government fielded the largest and best-equipped army and navy in the history of the world up to that point for four long years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/dilorenzo/dilorenzo31.html |title=Claremont's Court Historians by Thomas J. DiLorenzo |publisher=Lewrockwell.com |date=October 12, 2002 |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>}}

As for the 1861–1865 conflict, Wilson suggests it be referred to as "The War to Preserve Southern Independence". Fleming argues that secession was legal: {{quote|Those who hold the opinion (false and easy to refute) that the United States in 1860 were an amalgamated central state believe that the secession of [[South Carolina]] and the other Southern states was illegal, an act of wickedness that can be explained only by the desire of evil Southerners to defend slavery. Thus, in the upside-down and fact-free world of leftists like [[Harry Jaffa]], the war was a "civil war" between the citizens of the same state or, better yet, a rebellion. Abolitionists clearly did not believe this, because after the War, they insisted that Southern states had left the Union and needed to be reconstructed. Everybody knew that it is a basic principle of international law, going back to [[Hugo Grotius|Grotius]] at least, that in a confederated state the members have a right to leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Random_Thoughts.writeback |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 25, 2006 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927172901/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/hardright.cgi/Random_Thoughts.writeback |archivedate=September 27, 2006 }}</ref>}}

While endorsing "authentic federalism",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewamerican.com/tna/1997/vo13no08/vo13no08_supreme_court.htm |title=Judicial Tyranny |publisher=Thenewamerican.com |date=April 14, 1997 |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> Francis stopped short at supporting a contemporary return to Southern secessionism, saying it is impractical and that the main political line of division in the United States is not between the regions of North and South (insofar as such regions can still be said to exist) but between elite and nonelite.  He said that Middle Americans in both regions face the same threats.<ref>An Infantile Disorder, Chronicles, February 1998.</ref>

David Brooks, a neoconservative critic, says that paleoconservatives do not dream of seeing slavery reborn. Instead, he concludes that they link rural communities to a transcendent order and ancient institutions: {{quote|They do not shy away from expressing their true beliefs, and if they supported slavery they would probably say so. They merely believe in the social hierarchies. In those southern communities, they say, social roles were crucial to happiness and ordered sociability. "[[Aristotle]] recognized that a well-ordered society protected an ascending order of good through the institutionalization of rank", Fleming and co-author [[Paul Gottfried]] wrote in their book ''The Conservative Movement''. They are talking about the social pecking order in old-time towns—the folks who live on the hill, the merchants on Main Street, the village idiot on the green. On a larger scale, the paleocons contrast the virtues of the republic with the corruptions of empire. The empire throws its weight around in the world; the republic minds its own business.<ref name="Buchananism"/>}}

===Fusionism===
Many first-generation paleoconservatives were ''[[National Review]]'' supporters, but drifted away as the magazine was seen as becoming neoconservative{{efn|The paleoconservatives' dispute with [[William F. Buckley Jr.]] is described in {{harvnb|Gottfried|1993}}.}} starting in the 1970s.{{sfn|Gottfried|1993}}{{page number needed|date=January 2018}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstthings.com/ftissues/ft9605/opinion/thistime.html |title=The End of Neoconservatism |first=James |last=Nuechterlein |publisher=First Things |date=May 1996 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061214182102/http://www.firstthings.com/ftissues/ft9605/opinion/thistime.html |archivedate=December 14, 2006 }}</ref> ''Chronicles'' founder [[Leopold Tyrmand]] complained that the movement gave political solutions to cultural problems.{{sfn|Gottfried|1993|p=50}}

Open hostility broke out in the mid-1980s and was never resolved.{{sfn|Gottfried|1993}}{{page needed|date=January 2018}} Some paleoconservatives argued that [[fusionism]] failed<ref name="(Con)fusion on the Right"/> and suggested a new alliance on the right to stand outside the neoconservative consensus.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://antiwar.com/raimondo/book1.html| title=The Old Right and the Future of Conservatism| first= Patrick J.| last= Buchanan}}</ref> Buchanan stated that "We are old church and old right, anti-imperialist and anti-interventionist, disbelievers in ''Pax Americana''".<ref name="Buchananism"/><ref>[http://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/what-is-left-what-is-right/ "What is Left? What is Right?"]. ''[[The American Conservative]]''</ref>

The [[Intercollegiate Studies Institute]] (ISI) still follows the old fusionism.{{sfn|Edwards|2003|loc=ch.&nbsp;6}} It showcases both neoconservative and Old Right ideas, such as [[anti-interventionism]], limited government and cultural regionalism, in its publications and conferences. While it favors free-market solutions it tends to recognize the limitations of the market, or as economist [[Wilhelm Röpke]] says, "the market is not everything". ISI scholarship includes analysis of [[agrarianism|agrarian]] and [[distributist]] works, along with the idea of an "humane economy".<ref>See, for example, {{harvnb|Röpke|1998}}.</ref>

One fusionist, [[James Burnham]], influenced paleocons, especially Francis. Gottfried said that the two men believed that social forces create ideologies—and that "moral visions are the mere accompaniments of the process by which classes make themselves economically dominant and try to control other groups".{{sfn|Gottfried|1999|p=63}}

===International parallels===
As paleoconservatism germinated as a reaction to neoconservatism,{{sfn|Scotchie|2017a|p=1}} most of its development as a distinct political tendency under that name has been in the United States, although there are parallels in the traditional Old Right of other Western nations. French conservatives such as [[Jean Raspail]]{{sfn|Williamson|2004|pp=265–270}} and British conservatives such as [[Enoch Powell]],{{sfn|Buchanan|2006|pages=187–190}} [[Peter Hitchens]],{{sfn|Hitchens|1999}} [[Antony Flew]] (whom the Rockford Institute awarded the Ingersoll Prize),<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Flew |first=Antony |author-link=Antony Flew |date=July 1999 |title='Social' Justice Is Not Justice |url=https://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/1999/July/23/7/magazine/article/10830007/ |url-access=subscription |magazine=Chronicles |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> [[John Betjeman|Sir John Betjeman]],{{sfn|Watson|1985|p=54}}<!-- From Watson 1985: "Sir John Betjeman, a real conservative unimpressed by the promise of Neo-Conservatism, reserved the term "business executive" for his moments of bitterest disdain." --> and [[Roger Scruton|Sir Roger Scruton]]<ref name="The Joy of Conservatism">{{cite web |last=Scruton |first=Roger |author-link=Roger Scruton |date=January 2006 |title=The Joy of Conservatism: An Interview with Roger Scruton |url=http://www.newpantagruel.com/2006/01/the_joy_of_cons.php |dead-url=yes |interviewer-last=Goss |interviewer-first=Maxwell |work=The New Pantagruel |publisher=Pantagruel Press |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061114121053/http://www.newpantagruel.com/2006/01/the_joy_of_cons.php?page=all |archive-date=November 14, 2006 |access-date=January 27, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> as well as Scruton's ''[[Salisbury Review]]'' and [[Derek Turner (journalist)|Derek Turner]]'s ''[[Quarterly Review]]'',<ref>edited by [[Derek Turner (journalist)|Derek Turner]], a [http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/January2001/0101Turner.htm contributor] to [[Chronicles (magazine)|''Chronicles'']] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070501052631/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/January2001/0101Turner.htm |date=May 1, 2007 }}</ref>{{verification failed|date=January 2018}} along with Australia's ''Sydney Traditionalist Forum''<ref>"[http://sydneytrads.com/ ''SydneyTrads - Weblog of the Sydney Traditionalist Forum'']</ref> and ''Edmund Burke's Club'' <ref>{{cite web |title=Edmund Burke's Club |url=http://edmundburkesclub.org.au/|publisher=Edmund Burke's Club |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> all emphasize skepticism, stability and the Burkean inheritance and may be considered broadly sympathetic to paleoconservative values.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} For example, Hitchens wrote in opposition to the [[Iraq War]]: {{quote|There is nothing conservative about war. For at least the last century war has been the herald and handmaid of socialism and state control. It is the excuse for censorship, organized lying, regulation and taxation. It is paradise for the busybody and the [[wikt:nark|nark]]. It damages family life and wounds the Church. It is, in short, the ally of everything summed up by the ugly word "progress".<ref>From {{cite web| url= http://pugpig.spectator.co.uk/comic/not-in-our-name/| title= Not in Our Name| first= Peter| last= Hitchens| date= 29 March 2003| deadurl= yes| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160208004203/http://pugpig.spectator.co.uk/comic/not-in-our-name/| archivedate= February 8, 2016| df= mdy-all}}</ref>}}

Note the [[One Nation (Australia)|One Nation]] movement in 1990s Australia,<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Stove |first=R.&nbsp;J. |author-link=R. J. Stove |date=July 1997 |title=The Iron Lady Down Under |url=https://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/1997/July/21/7/magazine/article/10836804/ |url-access=subscription |magazine=Chronicles |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> Germany's [[Junge Freiheit]]<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Gottfried |first=Paul |author-link=Paul Gottfried |date=January 2003 |title=A Welcome Anniversary |url=https://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/2003/January/27/1/magazine/article/10826340/ |url-access=subscription |magazine=Chronicles |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> and Italy's [[Lega Nord]]<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Carosa |first=Alberto |date=July 2004 |title=Letter From Italy: 'Peaceful' Immigrants |url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/July2004/0704Carosa.html |dead-url=yes |magazine=Chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060718000541/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/Chronicles/July2004/0704Carosa.html |archive-date=July 18, 2006 |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> and compare the Russian dissidents [[Andrei Navrozov]]<ref>A corresponding editor to [[Chronicles (magazine)|''Chronicles'']] {{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/magazine.cgi/Yr%202006/August/Contents.html?seemore=y |publisher=Chronicles |date=August 2006 |title=Table of Contents |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061012062455/http://www.chroniclesmagazine.org/cgi-bin/magazine.cgi/Yr%202006/August/Contents.html?seemore=y |archivedate=October 12, 2006 |df= }} (see "Masthead" in lower-right corner of page)</ref> and [[Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn]].<ref>See for example his 1974 speech ''[http://www.columbia.edu/cu/augustine/arch/solzhenitsyn/livenotbylies.html Live Not By Lies] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060827211742/http://www.columbia.edu/cu/augustine/arch/solzhenitsyn/livenotbylies.html |date=August 27, 2006 }}''</ref>

==Neoconservatism==
{{main|Neoconservatism and paleoconservatism}}
Pat Buchanan calls neoconservatism "a globalist, interventionist, open-borders ideology".<ref>{{cite news |last=Carr |first=David |author-link=David Carr (journalist) |date=September 9, 2002 |title=For Buchanan, a New Pulpit and Target |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/09/business/media-for-buchanan-a-new-pulpit-and-target.html |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> The paleoconservatives argue that the "neocons" are illegitimate interlopers in the conservative movement. In 1986,<ref name="gottfried48">{{cite web|url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/gottfried/gottfried48.html |title=Fatuous and Malicious by Paul Gottfried |website=Archive.lewrockwell.com |date=March 28, 2003 |accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> the historian Stephen Tonsor, who rejects the label "paleoconservative",<ref name=nr2003>{{cite magazine |last=Frum |first=David |author-link=David Frum |year=2003 |title=Unpatriotic Conservatives: A War against America |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/frum/frum031903.asp |magazine=National Review |volume=55 |issue=6 |location=New York |pages=32–40 |issn=0028-0038 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031205032059/http://www.nationalreview.com/frum/frum031903.asp |archive-date=December 5, 2003 |access-date=January 27, 2018 |deadurl=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref> said: {{quote|It has always struck me as odd, even perverse, that former Marxists have been permitted, yes invited, to play such a leading role in the Conservative movement of the twentieth century. It is splendid when the town whore gets religion and joins the church. Now and then she makes a good choir director, but when she begins to tell the minister what he ought to say in his Sunday sermons, matters have been carried too far.<ref name="tonsor">{{cite web|url=http://novaemilitiae.squarespace.com/periodic-musings-blog/2006/7/11/the-traditionalist-conservatives-revolt-against-modernity.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 11, 2006 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070429130925/http://novaemilitiae.squarespace.com/periodic-musings-blog/2006/7/11/the-traditionalist-conservatives-revolt-against-modernity.html |archivedate=April 29, 2007 }}</ref>}}

